# DNOO Enhancement — Quick Familiarization Tasks (Non-technical)

Source document: specs/001-dnoo-enhancement/internal.md

## Plain-language summary (rephrased)

### What this project is
This is a follow-up improvement project for two systems:
- ADMS: the system used to run and manage the power distribution network.
- GIS: the map-based system that stores the “source of truth” for network assets and locations.

### Why it is needed now
GIS and ADMS were launched in 2025 under tight time and resource limits. To meet deadlines, some temporary fixes and manual workarounds were used.
Now, business users are reporting gaps compared to the old GIS, and there are new needs from changed business processes and regulatory requirements.

### What the project is trying to achieve (in simple terms)
- Fix high-priority gaps and pain points.
- Reduce manual steps that waste time and can cause mistakes.
- Keep data accurate and systems stable.
- Prepare for future changes (especially the 22kV network).

### What is NOT included
- Cleaning up old legacy data problems that were not handled before.
- Enhancements triggered directly by the Enlight (ERP) project.
- “Product enhancements” or unfinished bugs from the original GIS project.
- Broad integration work beyond GIS and ADMS.

### What will be delivered (high level)
ADMS improvements (examples):
- Better outage workflow integration.
- Support for 22kV operations over time.
- More automation for switching plan updates.
- Better handling of complex outage scenarios.
- Compliance-related workflow improvements.

GIS improvements (5 main areas):
1) Excavation permit improvements: include more land data and export what’s needed automatically.
2) Circuit reporting improvements: make cable length updates automatic and produce better reports for replacement planning.
3) CCI inventory automation: track which cables are in which tunnels/bridges and keep reports updated automatically.
4) 22kV network configuration: make GIS able to display and manage 22kV assets correctly.
5) Automate “manual workarounds”: reduce repeated manual steps (for example, auto-generate Name/Alias fields for ADMS).

### High-level timeline (what to expect)
- Planning & design happens first.
- Development/configuration follows.
- Testing (SIT/UAT/Pen Test) follows development.
- There is an “Enlight freeze period” that may impact timing (still TBC).
- Later phases include a 22kV pilot and then full deployment/optimization.

### Who is involved (governance and teams)
- PEC (Project Executive Committee) provides oversight.
- PMO (PAT) provides governance and direction.
- Project Manager leads delivery.
- Two main delivery workstreams: ADMS and GIS.
- Shared support functions: Infra, Enterprise Architect, Cyber Security, Data Services, System Custodian, System Owner.
- Vendor (SE) supports delivery (names listed in the source document).

### Key risks (simple view)
- Dependencies on Enlight testing environments and timing.
- Vendor capacity and scheduling risks.
- Integration risks across multiple systems.
- Data synchronization issues between ADMS and GIS.
- Compliance/safety readiness.
- User adoption and training.
- Performance/scalability.

## Task checklist (do these to get up to speed quickly)

### A. Understand the “why” and boundaries
- [ ] Read “Background” and “Rationale / Why Now” in internal.md.
- [ ] Confirm the 6 overall goals in plain words with the business owner.
- [ ] Confirm “Out of Scope” items so expectations are clear.

### B. Understand what will be delivered
- [ ] Review ADMS deliverables list; highlight which are most urgent.
- [ ] Review GIS deliverables (5 areas); write 1 sentence per item about the business benefit.
- [ ] Confirm which deliverables are mandatory for regulatory compliance.

### C. Confirm who decides what (governance)
- [ ] Note PEC members and what they approve.
- [ ] Note PMO (PAT) members and what they approve.
- [ ] Note the Project Manager(s) and their day-to-day decision scope.

### D. Validate timeline assumptions
- [ ] Confirm what “M” means (project start month) and who owns the schedule.
- [ ] Confirm the Enlight freeze period timing and its impact.
- [ ] Confirm when the 22kV pilot is expected.

### E. Review risks and what to watch
- [ ] Review the risk table; pick the top 3 risks to track weekly.
- [ ] Confirm owners for each mitigation (who will do the action).

### F. Fill the missing “mandatory” spec parts (so the document is complete)
- [ ] Write 3–6 user stories (P1/P2/P3) in non-technical language.
- [ ] Turn deliverables into Functional Requirements (FR-001, FR-002, …).
- [ ] Add Non-Functional Requirements (performance, security, reliability, compliance).
- [ ] Define Success Criteria (measurable outcomes).
- [ ] Capture Open Questions (anything unclear or waiting on TBC).

### G. Prepare for stakeholder alignment
- [ ] Create a 10-question list for your first alignment meeting (scope, priorities, timeline, risks).
- [ ] Agree on a weekly reporting format (1 page: progress, next steps, risks, decisions needed).
